xnb: sinatʉ kari Cai'ingwxn congtong taihio seho moso'ʉvʉ maraini na Iencominco
english: President Tsai Ing-wen's Apology to the Indigenous Peoples on Behalf of the Government.

xnb: 'esi na niaca'iva co maposan orocin cenana taniara miaasoa soni. niarisinata na sienfa soa "sanpao" kisʉʉn ia, pati'ʉnʉ'ʉnʉʉn co "Iencomin" kisʉʉn. soa sipatanganai isi ia, ka'anʉ co makai miana, 'ona ti'ingi 'esi masicoro'o 'imiin. parasorocoʉn co Cao Vovorong tamna nganai, "masiiraro caoin" soa 'ʉnai Taiwan isi. moociri kita nesi. soni, te kita mosoroosoro kiracʉkʉʉcʉkʉ. te ko taihio seho, masiikosa na kavangvang Cao Vovorong. 'ona nipamocia, te kita mangocono navongo moso'ʉvʉ. niaca'iva co osʉʉpatʉ mʉna cenana isi. nimoro'inasʉ kamo. koo kamo katʉtʉnʉn arakokonoʉn. te ko taihio seho, maraini misee kamoa.
english: On this day 22 years ago, the term "shanbao" (mountain people) in the Additional Articles of our Constitution was replaced with the proper name: "indigenous people." This correction not only did away with a discriminatory term, but also highlighted the status of indigenous peoples as Taiwan's "original owners." From this basis, today, we are taking another step forward. To all indigenous peoples of Taiwan: On behalf of the government, I express to you our deepest apology. For the four centuries of pain and mistreatment you have endured, I apologize to you on behalf of the government.

xnb: potococoro ko. mataarava masini. 'esi na aracʉvʉrʉa mita namoriongo. 'ona pa cao pacʉpʉngʉ, namone'i maraini misee. isi soa vanai mako, tia taihio seho maraini kamoa misee. miana soa ka'anʉ katʉtʉnʉn. nokai, cao cocomeni tamna moro'inasʉ. 'ona cao pacʉpʉngʉ, masiiraro tia makaasoa misee. vanai kita tia moociri nesi, te kita pati'ʉnʉ'ʉnaʉn cʉpʉngʉ makaasoa.
english: I know that even now, there are some around us who see no need to apologize. But that is the most important reason why I am representing the government to issue this apology today. To see what was unfair in the past as a matter of course, or to treat the pain of other ethnic peoples as an unavoidable part of human development, this is the first mindset that we, standing here today, resolve to change and overturn.

xnb: 'oroopaca kita ka'anʉ rangrang kari. tomatootoro neni vanai tia maraini misee na Cao Vovorong? 'ʉnai Taiwan isi. miaa niaca'iva co osʉʉpata mʉna cenana, 'ona co cao monoon nesi comacʉvʉrʉ. cao iisoa, masiiraro 'esi takacicini comacʉvʉrʉ. 'ona takacicini tamna kari, oʉnhoa, niorina, siacʉvʉrʉ 'acangʉ 'ʉnai. macovongo, koo pa ngoani pakiitoro, 'ona cao cocomeni iaavato
english: Let me put in simple terms why we are apologizing to the indigenous peoples. Four hundred years ago, there were already people living in Taiwan. These first inhabitants lived their lives and had their own languages, cultures, customs, and domains. But then, without their consent, another group of people arrived on these shores, and in the course of history, took everything from the first inhabitants who, on the land they have known most intimately, became displaced, foreign, non-mainstream, and marginalized.

xnb: na 'ʉnai isi. makaasoa co, soa marivivini iaavato cao ia, makai toiisoa co caoin 'ʉnai isi. soa masiiraro kasian cao ia, niara'akia co to'onain. makai co cao cocomeni, ka'anʉ co ngaca'ʉ 'ʉnai, toiisoa kacikicikiringa cao. 'ʉna ocani tʉmʉkʉ cao. soa vanain aratatia ia, manasʉ niaranai cao cocomeni tamna moro'inasʉ. noo ka'aniin kita makasi, tia katʉtʉnʉ soa koka. makai isi niaca'iva co cao comacʉvʉrʉ, te kita taramanʉngʉ, masicocoro vanain. makasoa co, soa seho ia, tia vanai nipaicaa iisoa. mangocono pacʉpʉcʉpʉngʉ neni nipamocia. isi soa vanai mako tia moociri nesi. 'ona ocani sinatʉ "Taiwan tongsʉ" kisʉʉn.
english: The success of one ethnic people can be built on the suffering of another. Unless we deny that we are a country of justice, we must face up to this history. We must tell the truth. And then, most importantly, the government must genuinely reflect on this past. This is why I stand here today.

xnb: sinatʉ iisoa ngoain tamna to'oroa kari, 'ona makasi, "aranai miana, 'akia niarisinata poiisoa nipaicaa miana. cao Hʉran kani pananai, Cʉng sʉʉ kani maporai, Cingtai kani nipotokikio." masiiraro makaasia Nakasaiana tamna siacʉ'ʉraa. soa Cao Vocorong ia, miaa 'esi pa niaca'iva meetosa cenana miana, 'esi co 'ʉnai isi. 'ona co macakoarʉ oʉnhoa mataa macʉrang, 'apacovongo nanamo. nakai 'apaica maa kita takacicini tamna siacʉ'ʉraa. marisinatʉ nipaicaa miana. vanai isi, te ko taihio seho, masiikosa na Cao Vovorong maraini misee.
english: There is a book called "The General History of Taiwan" published in 1920. In its foreword are these words: "Taiwan had no history. The Dutch pioneered it, the Koxinga Kingdom built it, and the Qing Empire managed it." This is a typical Han view of history. The truth is that indigenous peoples have been here for thousands of years, with rich culture and wisdom that have been passed down through generations. But we only know to write history from the perspective of the dominant. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

xnb: Hʉran mataa Cʉng cʉng kong tamna seho. nimiapacai 'Oria mataa marisoacʉ nopasʉ. miaa Cingcao citai, paira 'ona tatia mosocara'ʉ macangini. miaa Ripoon citai, mosikarʉ na to'onaa Cao Vovorong 'oma'atipi. mataarava co Minkoo tamna seho. tia kani 'apatʉnʉn mataa namanamarʉ siacʉvʉrʉ. makaasoa osʉʉpatʉ mʉna cenana. kavangvang soa niivato na Taiwan seho. 'oroopaca nanto macangini, marisoacʉ 'ʉnai. miakaka Cao Vovorong tamna kenri. vanai isi, te ko taihio seho, masiikosa na Cao Vovorong maraini misee.
english: The Dutch and the Koxinga Kingdom massacred and exploited the Pingpu ethnic group. The Qing Empire presided over bloody confrontations and suppression. Colonial Japan put in place comprehensive savage policies. And the post- war ROC government undertook assimilation policies. For 400 years, every regime that has come to Taiwan has brutally violated the rights of indigenous peoples through armed invasion and land seizure. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

xnb: 'oroopaca niorina Cao Vovorong matimanʉngʉ tanasʉn.'oroopaca kangvang niorina macʉrang matimanʉngʉ korakorapʉ. nakai, miaa toiisoa masini tamna koka. niara'akia Cao Vovorong masiiraro tia takacicini tamna kenri. nimitʉrʉ aranai miana copoongana tanasnʉ. ka'anʉ potococoroʉn ngoani tamna kenri. vanai isi, te ko taihio seho, masiikosa na Cao Vovorong moso'ʉvʉ maraini misee.
english: Indigenous peoples maintain tribal order according to traditional customs, and ecological balance according to traditional wisdom. But in the process of modern state-building, indigenous peoples lost the right to steer their own course and govern their own affairs. The fabric of traditional societies was torn apart, and the collective rights of peoples were not recognized. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

xnb: masiiraro 'ona Cao Vovorong tamna kari. nakai aranai miaa Ripoon citai, mataarava 1945 cenana. 'atipin seho, aka kani 'oroopaca takacicini tamna kari. makasoa co, te co morovangvang ma'acono kari Cao Vovorong. 'akia co kavangvang 'Oria tamna kari. maka'ʉna'ʉna seho, ka'anʉ kipaatʉsʉ maritakarʉ Cao Vovorong tamna oʉnhoa. vanai isi, te ko taihio seho, masiikosa na Cao Vovorong moso'ʉvʉ maraini misee.
english: Indigenous peoples had their own languages. However, with Japanese rule aiming to assimilate and turn all into imperial subjects, and with the ROC government banning tribal languages after 1945, indigenous peoples' languages suffered great losses. Most Pingpu languages have disappeared. Successive governments have been negligent in the protection of indigenous cultures. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

xnb: cenana meesoa. ka'anʉ tavara'ʉ cao Iami. mosakasakao ovʉngʉn 'inia hʉferiao. miakaka tina'an cao ka'inia. vanai isi, te ko taihio seho, masiikosa na Iami, moso'ʉvʉ marai misee. soa niaranai 'ʉnai cocomeni mosikarʉ na Taiwan, ngoai soa monoon na sipo 'Oria. nimo'oroo'oro ara'akia co ngoani tamna nganai. vanai isi, te ko masiikosa na 'Oria, moso'ʉvʉ maraini misee.
english: Without the knowledge of the Yami tribe, the government stored nuclear waste on Orchid Island. Tribe members on the island had to suffer the negative consequences. For this, I apologize to the Yami people on behalf of the government. Ever since outsiders began arriving in Taiwan, the Pingpu ethnic group on the western plains have born the brunt of the impact. One ruling power after another eroded the individual and collective identities of the Pingpu ethnic group. For this, I apologize to the Pingpu ethnic group on behalf of the government.

xnb: mosoroosoro co minco. arivariʉn seho Cao Vovorong tamna niarisosonaa. 'ona seho tamna nipakitoroa, 'ona nikipatʉsaa. soni, 'ona co kita "Ienco minco cipʉnfa." nakai horeco isi, ka'anʉ kasakʉnʉʉn seho. ka'anʉ kita mara'an potokikio, ka'anʉ marivangvang, ka'anʉ maningcao coro. vanai isi, te ko taihio seho, masiikosa na Cao Vovorong moso'ʉvʉ maraini misee.
english: After the democratic transition, the country began to respond to the appeals of indigenous movements. The government made certain promises and efforts. Today, we have an Indigenous Peoples Basic Law that is quite advanced. However, government agencies have not given sufficient weight to this law. Our actions have not been fast enough, comprehensive enough or sound enough. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

xnb: makasi kita "tooyen oʉnhoa" kani soa Taiwan. nakai, mataarava masini. Cao Vovorong tamna tina'an, kiatootoro, siacʉvʉrʉ nopasʉ, marivivini pa na ka'anʉ Cao Vovorong. 'ona pa, koo pa tarasangai taranʉkʉpai, mataa taracoro'oʉn na Cao Vovorong. ka'anʉ pa mosotanpʉ nipotokikioa seho. moro'inasʉ mataa masange co Cao Vovorong tamna cʉpʉngʉ. vanai isi, te ko taihio seho, masiikosa na Cao Vovorong moso'ʉvʉ maraini misee.
english: Taiwan is known as a culturally diverse society. But even today, indicators on health, education, economic livelihood, political participation and more still show gaps between indigenous and non- indigenous peoples. Meanwhile, stereotypes and even discrimination against indigenous peoples have not gone away. The government has not done enough, so indigenous peoples have suffered pain and frustration unknown to other ethnic peoples. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

xnb: ka'anʉ mosotanpʉ nikipatʉsaa mita. mkaasoa namonamo co, koo makacang mati'ʉnʉʉ'ʉna. moro'inasʉ iisoa, 'esi pa 'inia mataarava masini. cocoro maraini! soni moso'ʉvʉ maraini misee. manasʉ nimaca'ivi co miaranao takananga. nakai, soa iai ia, te co pananai arakaranana. ka'anʉ ko pacʉpʉngʉ, osʉʉpatʉ mʉna co cenana. niro'inasaa Cao Vovorong, tia vanai ocani sinatʉ, ocani maraini misee kari, tavara'ʉ co ara'akia. nakai, 'ona cʉpʉngʉ mako. kamʉcʉ soa maraini misee soni, tavara'ʉ cocoro pakamamanʉng kitana kavangvang.
english: Our efforts have fallen short, and succeeding generations have been blind to this inadequacy. Because of this, your hardship has continued to this day. For this we are truly sorry. Today's apology is long overdue, but it is a beginning. I do not expect any one speech or phrase of apology to wipe away four centuries of pain and suffering by the indigenous peoples. But I do hope with all my heart that today's apology will set this country and all its people on the path towards reconciliation.

xnb: te ko 'oroopaca Cao Vovorong tamna macʉrang. tomatootoro neni vanai kita soni tia arakokono. 'ona Tayaro tamna kari, soa "cʉnsiang" ia, "Balay" kisʉʉn. soa "hʉcie" ia, "Sbalay" kisʉʉn. tia po'oro'oroʉn "S" misee, pokariikari co "Balay." kariin soa "cʉnsiang mataa hʉcie" ia, 'apacovongo cʉpʉngʉ iisoa. iimoa, soa cocoro tia 'aropamanʉngʉ ia, tia 'apaica marivoarʉ cocoro nipaicaa. makaosin ia, manasʉ te co 'ona ramangʉ makacʉkʉna.
english: Please allow me to shed light on this occasion with a piece of indigenous wisdom. In the Atayal language, truth is called "Balay," and reconciliation is called "Sbalay," so you simply add an "S" sound to "Balay." Truth and reconciliation are in fact two related concepts. In other words, only by facing the truth sincerely can reconciliation be attained.

xnb: na Cao Vovorong tamna oʉnhoa. noo 'onain cao nipaamoci na cao cocomeni. 'onain cʉpʉngʉ tia 'aropamanʉngʉ. soa mamarorang ia, tia maricovocovongo ngoani. noo matacovocovongo co ia, ka'anʉ makacʉng maripipining kari maraini misee. mo'oroo'oro pa marivovoarʉ takacicini tamna cʉpʉngʉ. marivivini 'apima co 'inia mamarorang. soa niaca'iva co ia maca'ivi co. isi soa kisaa "Sbalay."
english: In indigenous cultures, when a tribe member has offended another and intends to reconcile, an elder brings together the offender and the offended - not to produce a direct apology, but to allow each side to frankly share their inner journeys. When this truth-telling concludes, the elder calls for everyone to drink together, so that what is past is truly past. This is "Sbalay."

xnb: pacʉpʉngʉ ko, arakokono kita soni. kamʉcʉ ngoai soa seho mataa Cao Vovorong 'esi cocoro "Sbalay." soa niaca'iva co nipamocia, nipaicaa miana, arivovoarʉn mako pokariikari. nosoni, tangria mita Cao Vovorong, tia maripipining kangvang kari. ka'anʉ ko tavara'ʉ makasi kamo, iorosoo ko misee. nakai te ko makasi kamoa, osʉ'oo na tavaaronga soa kamʉcʉ tamna cʉpʉngʉ. soa nipamocia miana ia, ka'anʉ tia makaa'ʉna arapipining. koka isi, tia 'ona ocani taniara, cocoro masiikosa na 'aropamanʉngʉ cacanʉ.
english: I hope today's occasion can be a "Sbalay" between the government and the indigenous peoples. I have spoken of past mistakes and truths the best I can, with nothing held back. In a moment, our indigenous friends will speak. I do not dare ask you to forgive, here and now. But I sincerely ask you to sustain the hope that past wrongs will not be repeated, and that one day, this country can see true reconciliation.

xnb: soa soni ia, 'esi pa maa tia pananai. tia kara cocoro 'aropamanʉngʉ, seho soa tia cʉ'ʉraa. ka'anʉ Cao Vovorong mataa 'Oria. tavara'ʉ ko, ka'anʉ mosotanpʉ 'inmaamia ivici pokariikari. soa nipotokikioa na Cao Vovorong, iisoa soa tia cocoro 'aropamʉnʉngʉ koka isi.
english: Today is only a beginning. The duty for reconciliation lies not with the indigenous peoples and the Pingpu ethnic group, but with the government. I know that words of apology alone are not enough. What we actually do for the indigenous peoples will decide whether reconciliation succeeds or stumbles.

xnb: te ko moon nesi marivovoarʉ kari. na sikara Congtong fo, tia 'apociri "Ienco minco risʉ cʉng'ii mataa risʉ coansing cʉng'ii oiyenhoi." te ko 'oroopaca Congtong tamna nganai marivivici. makariikari mataa Cao Vovorong tamna taihio.kenkio tia potokikioa koka.
english: Therefore, I am here to announce that we are setting up an Indigenous Historical Justice and Transitional Justice Commission under the Presidential Office. As the head of state, I will serve as convener and work hand in hand with tribal representatives to pursue historical justice. We will also discuss, on the basis of equality, the future policy direction of this country.

xnb: miaa tia co aratʉkʉnʉ, makasi coma voravorao, marʉngʉcai co ko, maromanʉngʉ misee.
english: Before I left, my uncle praised me for growing taller and becoming more handsome.

xnb: makasi ko, "noo manʉng co 'acipi, ivataa kangvang na tanasa mia."
english: I said, "When your foot gets better, come to our house next time and visit us."

xnb: 2022 cenana, makarikari seho Yencomin tamna nipinsio tʉni arisinatʉn Cao Vovorong tamna nganai.
english: In 2022, the government announced that indigenous identification cards can include tribal names separately.

xnb: kesoniʉn mako miaranao co makinee na seho, nipinsio tia marisinatʉ "caokia nganai" soa nanmaroa porako Pa'ʉ.
english: I interviewed Pa'ʉ, a young tribal member who has long been advocating for the inclusion of tribal names on identification cards.

xnb: 'aropatotoro kim na tarasangara isi, tia mokosa tanasa in kesoni 'inia.
english: We had arranged to visit his home this holiday for the interview.

xnb: miaa kesoni 'inia, siokai ngoain niaranai nano soa nganai in. marivici pa 'ikoa tarakanangʉ cao tanasa in, mataa ngoain tamna porako.
english: During the interview, he introduced to me the origin of his name and also introduced me to his family and tribe.

xnb: kesoniʉn mako, miseni manatʉrʉ cʉpʉngʉ tia mati'ʉnʉ'ʉna nganai, cʉngnan niarisinatʉa 'esi nano aka?
english: I asked him why he insisted on changing his name. Wasn't the old registration method sufficient?

xnb: makasi Pa'ʉ: "'oropaca Yencomin kari nganai ia, cocoro nganai mita. nganai mako 'esi 'inia coko mita, cʉpʉngana mita, tina'an nganara mita, kamʉcʉ arakacaoa coakia tʉni mʉtʉa takacicini tamna nganai."
english: Noami Kulas said, "The names written in indigenous languages are our true names. My name represents our ethnic group, our family, our identity. I hope more fellow tribespeople can reclaim their own names."

xnb: miʉra kipapa ko tamo nanakʉ mokosa tamia'aa mapopo'a. niarivici tamo 'itomoro tinakacicini momʉkʉ natʉngʉ. kamanʉngʉ pa Cao Vovorong tamna sa'o'o kʉkʉnʉa.
english: Yesterday, I went to the market with my grandmother to set up a stall. My grandmother brought a lot of vegetables that she grew herself and also prepared indigenous cuisine for everyone.

xnb: ka'anmanʉn cao tamo tamna tamia'aa. manman mataa 'arikoriki kacaoa cao po'a. kacaoa kangvang cao kotanamʉ nipo'ocipia kee kʉkʉnʉa.
english: Everyone loved my grandmother's stall. Many people bought the chilis and African eggplants, and many people came to taste the dishes she cooked.

xnb: nipo'ocipia kee tariri mataa tipi cocoro sa'o'o, cinapa kee 'aramʉ vavoro, maricoco kacaoa 'okiako. matavʉnʉrʉ na ikim tamna tamia'aa.
english: The ferns and sticky rice she cooked were delicious, as well as the braised pork with maqaw pepper and wild boar meat. The flavors attracted many customers, and everyone lined up at our stall.

xnb: 'esiin po'icipi tamo, 'esi ko ciciri mariapa 'okiako. marisosona ko, "tinakacicini momʉkʉ natʉngʉ, koo pocanomoʉn savoana, ivataa po'a!"
english: While my grandmother was cooking, I was on the side attracting customers. I shouted, \The vegetables are self-grown

xnb: nonoman mia makacang vangvangʉʉn co mapo'a. makasi tamo, "vanai sii 'ona kaso moranʉ."
english: Our goods sold out quickly, and my grandmother said, \It's all thanks to your help.\""

xnb: matacovongo isi, takotavarʉ'ʉ ko poisoa karokaroa mataa kʉkʉnʉa macʉrʉng, takotavarʉ'ʉ pa cocoro mopacai soa mapo'a kasiopai.
english: Through this event, I learned about indigenous plants and food and experienced the hard work of running a stall.

xnb: comacʉ'ʉra tamo masakʉn niorina kʉkʉnʉa, cocoro ko porangatʉ mataa ma'inco.
english: Seeing my grandmother's passion for traditional food, I feel very proud and honored.
